{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b45941d1-d2ec-4f25-9f37-0d454729decf","content":"Here are the **3 MSBuild evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (`.csproj` line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"...\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to **walk the entire directory tree** on every evaluation. This is the most expensive pattern — cost scales with repo size, and it runs even for IDE design-time builds.\n\n**Fix:** Scope the glob to specific extensions/directories (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or remove it if not needed.\n\n---\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function (`.csproj` line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalls `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` **during evaluation**, adding synchronous disk I/O to every single evaluation pass (including IntelliSense refreshes). The `build-notes.txt` file itself warns about this.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target that runs at build time (e.g., inside a `<Target>`) rather than a top-level `<PropertyGroup>`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Deep chained imports (`level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`)\nThree levels of nested `<Import>` files, each importing the next. Each import adds XML parsing and evaluation overhead. While 3 levels is modest, this pattern tends to grow and compounds with the issues above since all imports are evaluated before any target runs.\n\n**Fix:** Flatten the chain — import a single `.props` file or use `Directory.Build.props` conventions.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The recursive glob and the `ReadAllText` property function are the two high-impact issues. Both execute on **every** evaluation pass (builds, restores, IDE refreshes), making them the primary bottlenecks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e3e3a869-ac4d-4528-80b2-dc057ea0e278","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe key issues I see:\n\n1. **Recursive wildcard glob (`**\\*.*`)** - Line 9 of the .csproj uses `**\\*.*` which causes MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is a well-known performance anti-pattern, especially in large repositories.\n\n2. **File I/O during evaluation via property functions** - Line 13 uses `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` which performs synchronous file I/O during project evaluation. \n\n3. **Deeply chained imports** - The level1.props → level2.props → level3.props chain creates three layers of imports, and each one adds evaluation overhead. Combined with the file I/O and glob patterns, this compounds the performance hit.\n\nThese three issues together are creating significant latency during every evaluation pass.","outputTokens":708,"requestId":"5C40:3ED17A:5E31628:67441CA:69F15D14"},"id":"688f3994-68a8-4828-87d0-1d89eb994dc9","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:21:40.583Z","parentId":"dc713336-bcd2-497a-a3b0-d98355d650c3"}
